Mason ISD will be distributing 4 tickets to every varsity football player, trainer, band member, and cheerleader today, Monday 8/24.

Due to the recent spike in COVID-19 cases in Mason County, Mason ISD has made the following changes to our Back to School Plan for 2020-21. On the link is the updated document with changes listed in red. Below is a summary of the changes for quick reference:

Effective August 11, 2020 masks or face coverings will be required for all teachers, staff or other campus visitors/volunteers while on campus. Masks or face coverings will also be required for all students in grades 5-12 who attend school On-Campus.
Mason ISD will continue to monitor the situation and re-evaluate this requirement every 6 weeks.
Updated "Close Contact" definition per the TEA Public Health Guidance released August 4th.
Removed 72 hours and replaced with 24 hours passed fever-free per the guidance from CDC and TEA Public Health Guidance.

https://www.masonisd.net/apps/pages/index.jsp?uREC_ID=1820157&type=d&pREC_ID=1980525

Don't Forget - College Night Zoom meeting on July 1st at 5:30 with Mrs. Canfield - where you will learn everything you need to know to apply to college from applications to resumes to transcripts to letters of recommendations to deadlines to test scores to scholarships and everything in between!

I have sent you and your senior a Google Calendar invite, which has the link to the Zoom Meeting. The meeting will be recorded, and I will send you the link to the recording after the meeting is over. However, you should definitely try to watch live, since I will be able to answer questions for you.

You can pick up your college handbook from my house anytime on Thursday or Friday of this week between 9:00 am and 6:00 pm. You will need these handbooks prior to the meeting.

This meeting is EXTREMELY IMPORTANT for EVERY STUDENT who is planning to apply to college! Please make plans to be at your computer to join the meeting.

post_text:
Good Morning! Just want to update everyone, we are still serving meals for our Summer Feeding program. We are here Monday thru Thursday from 8am until 10am. We continue to source out the best fresh fruit and veggie available. We have had some wonderful nectarines, oranges, apple slices and pears. We have fresh sliced cucumbers, celery, tomato cups and carrots coming in today and next week some peaches, apples and pears.

Please come by and see us and pick up meals for your kiddos! We Really appreciate everyone who takes the time to come by! This service is Free to all children 18 and younger, they do not have to be in school here or anywhere, they do not even have to reside in Mason. This is great for babysitters, grandparents, families who have visiting relatives or the Very busy parents.

Thank you again, we hope to see everyone. Take care and stay safe, Julie Parker

Pandemic Electronic Benefit Transfer (P-EBT) is a one-time food benefit for families who lost access to free or reduced-price meals due to school closures. Eligible P-EBT families will receive application instructions from schools in late May. The P-EBT application will open the first week of June.

P-EBT food benefits are for children who received SNAP food benefits for March 2020 and children who are certified for free or reduced-price school meals during the 2019-20 Texas school year. For more information, visit: hhs.texas.gov/PEBT

post_text:
From Mrs. Parker and the Cafeteria Staff:

I want to let everyone know that we Really appreciate everyone who takes the time to come pick up meals. We realize that it takes a bit of your valuable time to do this BUT we really are happy to see you and know that we are doing a little part in helping out our families.

Please remember that pick ups are Monday, Wednesday and Friday from 8-10 am. If you cannot get here until a bit after please text me, 325 218-2659 and I will be happy to have them ready for you.

Please stop by and see us and get some meals for your kiddos, it is such a pleasure for us to be able to provide this service to our families. Everything is individually wrapped and microwave ready to make things a bit easier and to supplement the groceries that you are able to get. It is perfect for grandparents and babysitters. Also, for parents who are already Really busy!

This service is free to all children 18 and younger and they do not have to be enrolled at Mason ISD.

Together we are strong, we are Mason! Thanks to all. Take care and stay safe! Julie Parker

Because the school closure has been extended until May 4, students in Mr. Pierce's Dual Credit English classes and Pre-AP English I classes, Mrs. Guice's Pre-AP English II classes, and all of Mrs. Pierce's junior English classes will need to pick up a novel from the school in order to complete school work during that time. We have scheduled a book pick-up so that students may quickly get their books while continuing to practice social distancing.

On Wednesday, April 8, from 12:45-2:00, Mr. Pierce will have three tables set up in the student parking lot at the high school. Students should just park, pick up their book, tell Mr. Pierce the number on the book, and leave.

If you or a representative cannot pick up the book during that time, please email your English teacher to make alternate arrangements.

From Coach Burns:
Students, if you have left your chromebook or textbooks at school during the extended break you will need to come pick them up as you begin online instruction. Online instruction will begin on Monday of next week (March 23rd) so you need to make sure that you have what you need to complete the work.

The building will only have one door open, the double doors by the auditorium, and nobody will be allowed inside the building. We will have a staff member at the door that will go to your locker or classroom to get the things that you need. Again, nobody will be allowed inside the building.

Times for picking up chromebooks / textbooks:
Thursday: 1pm - 3:30pm
Friday: 8am - 12pm

If you can't make it to the high school during these times or have a question then please call the office at 325-347-1122 ext 221.

Thanks for your understanding and patience,

post_text:
From Nurse Moneyhon:
Please encourage students to wash hands frequently throughout the day. This is the single best action that we can do to prevent illnesses. (There are some great YouTube videos for the little ones to watch before practicing.)
Do NOT come to school with a fever of 100.4 or more within the past 24 hours. This is without the use of fever reducing medications. You are at a greater risk of getting sicker and others are at a greater risk of you spreading the illness to them.
Keep unwashed hands away from your eyes, nose, and mouth. Use a tissue when available and dispose it properly.
When coughing, turn your head away from people AND cough into your elbow . Praise students for using correct germ etiquette. To decrease your risk of illness, it is best to avoid drinking and eating after your friends/family. We can all do our part to help clean our areas. Thank you for helping by cleaning frequently used items like door knobs and desks throughout the day.

Keep unwashed hands away from your eyes, nose, and mouth. Use a tissue when available and dispose it properly.

post_text: The VFW Legion in Mason sponsor an essay contest every year for juniors and seniors at MHS. This year Colby Brown won the contest with his essay. He received $200 and a chance to advance to the state and national level where he could win a $30,000 scholarship. Placing 2nd and winning $100 is Mackenzie Cano and 3rd place winner Alex Cope, received $50. Congratulations to these students.

post_text:
Mrs. Canfield and a large group of MHS students had the opportunity for a special campus visit to ASU yesterday. They ran into several MHS graduates including Lupe Callejas. She is in nursing school and was headed to do some skills tests. Thanks to dual credit, she was able to apply to nursing school during her first semester at ASU.

They also saw Bridgit Herrington in the library, who said that college was a lot easier than she thought it would be. She said her profs teach like Mr. Kahan! She learned so much in Mrs. Cope's class that her math class is easy, and they are doing fallacies in her speech class, which she already learned in Mr. Pierce's class. She is grateful to all of her MHS teachers.

Jason Harwell, Khristina Sanchez and Brooklyn Doss were spotted at lunch, Natalia Zapata at the Starbucks on campus and Alina Ordonez was in the library studying. And Amber Hengst showed us her ASU senior ring because she will graduate soon! MHS is doing good work! MHS is very proud of their students: past, present and future.

Here are some examples that are the result of hard work and dedication from Ms. Horton's high school art students.

üé®Art 1 and Art 2 made a collage out of found imagery on an 8x10 inch paper, then used the grid system to draw their collage on a 16x20 inch piece of paper. Art 1 could only use graphite pencil, Art 2 had to use colored pencil.
üé®Art 3 explored the idea of space in 2-D artwork, whether it be positive/negative space, perspectival space, illusion of depth, foreshortening, etc. They are encouraged to try an aspect that they have not used.
üé®Art 4 students are creating a self-directed body of work, 5 or 6 18x24 inch pieces that relate to an artist statement.
(Student names and classes are in the comments.)

post_text:
MHS will host FAFSA Night in the high school library
from 6:00-8:00 TONIGHT, Monday, October 21st.

A Financial Aid Officer from Angelo State University will be here to assist parents and students with any questions you have regarding filling out the FAFSA.

You will need to bring the following:
2018 tax returns (for parent and student, if the student filed)
Your social security number (parent and student)
Your FSA ID (for parent and student)
You can create your FSA ID by going to https://fsaid.ed.gov/npas/index.htm
You should do this at least one week before the meeting.
Parents who have already filled out the FAFSA for an older child will use their same FSA ID.
Parents, if you cannot attend the meeting, make sure to send your student to the meeting with this information. Your student can take care of this!

Also, it is important to remember that you will have to fill out the FAFSA every year that your student is in college.

post_text:
Who remembers the HONK PARADE? Immediately following the pep rally, there will be a honk parade through town. This is a tradition from Mason's past and is only permitted on special occasions. The last honk parade was when Fox Sports Southwest was in town for the DQ Big Game of the Week. It is important that you participate with great responsibility while you are having fun enjoying the memories you are making.

When pep rally ends, immediately line cars up BEHIND the fire truck that will be located on El Paso (by the Rock M). The fire truck will lead the parade through the town (Nuway, Movies, Mason Bank, Puncherdome, Lea Lou, Square Plate, and finally DQ). Drive SLOWLY and following all the traffic laws. At times, other vehicles not participating in the honk parade will have the right away so DO NOT CUT THEM OFF!

ENJOY the tradition and acknowledgment from the community members for your success and contributions to our great town!

post_text:
The administration at MHS wants to make parents aware of the serious risks from vaping or "juuling." It is estimated that 85% of teens have tried vaping, and there is no reason to believe that number is different for Mason High School.
We presented to the students facts and videos from news reports at an assembly this morning, and we want to also make parents aware of the dangers. Please talk to your student about this subject. We have shared the presentation with all students, so they can take it home and show parents. In the meantime, we have included some information from Johns Hopkins Medicine that is also included in our presentation.
If you believe your student is addicted, we are here to help.

MISD began pre-sale tickets for the Mason Puncher vs Wall Hawk game 8/21 at 9:00am at the Administration Building to reduce lines at the game. Tickets are $5 adults and $3 students.

Please refer to the picture for changes to parking for this particular game. The red lines represent barricades to the parking areas adjacent to the Community Center. These areas (BLUE) will be designated for handicapped parking and Fox Sports SW personnel. Regular parking and overflow parking (ORANGE) will be in the designated areas around the park. The driving range will not be used for parking so there is no need for us to shuttle. Fans who park in the overflow areas can simply walk the short distance to the PuncherDome.

We have secured extra bleachers that will seat an additional 400+ fans. Those bleachers will be set up in the end zone by the scoreboard on Tuesday, Aug. 27. We have also secured additional restrooms that will be located between the extra bleachers and the visitor stands. #ppnd

Eleven Mason FFA Chapter members attended the 91st Annual Texas FFA Convention held this summer at the Ft. Worth Convention Center. Those attending represented Mason as voting delegates during eight general sessions held throughout the week. Approximately 10,000 FFA members, parents, teachers, and guests attend the annual event. Selah Farmer participated in the Texas FFA Rodeo and finished thirteenth in the state in barrels. Congrats to her!

(bottom l-r) Isela Rodriguez, Desaree Bowie, Anyka Morquecho, Jessica Wartenbach, and Selah Farmer. (back l-r) Rylan Jordan, Alexandra Cope, Will Ince, Colby Brown, Tiffany Snow, and Alyssa DelToro.

Included in the photo are board members Julio Ramon, Treg Hudson, Tina Cantu-Navarro, Ryan Jordan, Kathryn Martin, Jeff Durst, Jim Bob Smith, also Coach Kade Burns, Superintendent John Schumacher, and players from the team Rudy Martinez, Rylan Jordan, Jase Eckert, Oscar Ortiz, John Benefield, Chandler Buntyn, Blake McLaughlin, Rudy Rochat, Tad Kirby, Daniel Gainer, Slone Stultz, Matthew Kerr, Josh Fluhmann, Zach Norman, Jason Harwell, Whitt Bierschwale, KO Tedder, JJ Ake and Lucas Martin. Congratulations again to Coach Burns, his amazing coaching staff and the team.
